s of students and redrawing school attendance zones, to more recent demands of community control of segregated schools. In all cases, the Board eventually pulled the plug in the face of resistance from more powerful stakeholders, and, starting in the 1970s, integration receded as a possible solution to educational inequality. In excavating the history of New York City school integration politics, in the halls of power and on the ground, Christopher Bonastia unearths the enduring white resistance to integration and the severe costs paid by Black and Latino students. This last decade has seen activists renew the fight for integration, but the war is still far from won.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aEducation and statezNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistory. 0aSchool integrationzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistory. 0aSegregation in educationzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh  aAfrican American history.  aBlack Freedom Struggles.  aNew York City.  acivil rights.  aeducation history.  aintegration.  aracial inequality.  asegregation.  asocial movements.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363198440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503631984423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503631984/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles